{
  "doc_id": "61407",
  "text": "Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy (HCM) is the most common monogenic cardiac disease, affecting approximately 1 in 500 individuals [CITATION_1] . HCM usually involves the mitral valve (MV), with intrinsic abnormalities, such as leaflet thickening and/or elongation, anomalous mitral papillary muscles or chordae, direct papillary muscle insertion onto the mitral leaflet, chordal rupture and MV prolapse [CITATION_2] . Excessive leaflet tissue, anterior displacement of the MV apparatus and chordal abnormalities also play a primary role in the systolic anterior motion (SAM) of the MV and left ventricular outflow tract (LVOT) obstruction [CITATION_3] . Mitral regurgitation (MR) in HCM is either caused by valve distortion as a consequence of SAM and/or is secondary to MV structural abnormalities.",
